Here is the RDF graph with instances and data about the property appraisal from the given input text, using the provided ontology:

<ontology>
@prefix rdf: <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#> .
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .
@prefix xsd: <http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#> .
@prefix mf: <http://example.org/mf> .

<mf:CollegeCourtyard> a <mf:Property> ;
    <mf:hasName> "College Courtyard Apartments & Raider Housing" ;
    <mf:hasAppraisal> <mf:CollegeCourtyard_Appraisal> .

<mf:CollegeCourtyard_Appraisal> a <mf:PropertyAppraisal> ;
    <mf:hasLandValue> "Not Utilized" .

</ontology>

In this RDF graph, we have created an instance <mf:CollegeCourtyard> of the class <mf:Property> to represent the "College Courtyard Apartments & Raider Housing" property. We have also created an instance <mf:CollegeCourtyard_Appraisal> of the class <mf:PropertyAppraisal> to represent the appraisal for this property.

The property <mf:hasName> is used to assign the name "College Courtyard Apartments & Raider Housing" to the <mf:CollegeCourtyard> instance. The property <mf:hasAppraisal> is used to link the <mf:CollegeCourtyard> instance to its appraisal instance <mf:CollegeCourtyard_Appraisal>.

Within the <mf:CollegeCourtyard_Appraisal> instance, we have used the property <mf:hasLandValue> to assign the value "Not Utilized" to the land value, based on the information provided in the input text.
